\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Hilbert's Nullstellensatz
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In this section, we will explore the correspondence between ideals and varieties.
 We will prove the Nullstellensatz, a celebrated theorem which identifies
 exactly which ideals correspond to varieties.
 This will allows us to construct a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

dictionary
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 between geometry and algebra, whereby any statement about varieties can
 be translated into a statement about ideals (and conversely).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To get things started, we ask the question: for which ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

 do we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}(I)=\emptyset$
\end_inset

? Clearly we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}\left(\langle1\rangle\right)=\emptyset$
\end_inset

, but this isn't the only case.
 For instance, if we take 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle x^{2}+1\rangle$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}[x]$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}(I)=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, if we replace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}(I)=\{\pm i\}\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 Are there any proper ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}[x]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}(I)=\emptyset$
\end_inset

? No: Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a proper ideal.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}[x]$
\end_inset

 is a PID, we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle f\rangle$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathbb{C}[x]$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 has degree 
\begin_inset Formula $d>0$
\end_inset

.
 It follows from the fundamental theorem of algebra that we can factor 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $f=(x-\alpha)g$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is a polynomial of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $d-1$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\mathbf{V}(I)$
\end_inset

, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}(I)\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

One difference between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 is algebraically closed, and as the previous paragraph indicates, this
 is the reason why we can find a proper ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}[x]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}(I)=\emptyset$
\end_inset

, but can't find such an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}[x]$
\end_inset

.
 We will give a generalization of this fact in the theorem below, but first
 we need a lemma.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemmataylor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 be polynomials in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x_{1},\dots,x_{n}+\varepsilon)=f(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})+\varepsilon g(x_{1},\dots,x_{n}),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $m=ax_{1}^{\alpha_{1}}\cdots x_{n}^{\alpha_{n}}$
\end_inset

 is a term of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{n}>0$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
ax_{1}^{\alpha_{1}}\cdots x_{n-1}^{\alpha_{n-1}}(x_{n}+\varepsilon)^{\alpha_{n}} & =ax_{1}^{\alpha_{1}}\cdots x_{n-1}^{\alpha_{n-1}}\left(x_{n}^{\alpha_{n}}+\varepsilon x_{n}^{\alpha_{n}-1}+\cdots+\varepsilon^{\alpha_{n}}\right)\\
 & =ax_{1}^{\alpha_{1}}\cdots x_{n-1}^{\alpha_{n-1}}x_{n}^{\alpha_{n}}+ax_{1}^{\alpha_{1}}\cdots x_{n-1}^{\alpha_{n-1}}\left(\varepsilon x_{n}^{\alpha_{n}-1}+\cdots+\varepsilon^{\alpha_{n}}\right)\\
 & =m+\varepsilon h,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is some polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now write express 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 as a sum of its terms 
\begin_inset Formula $f=m_{1}+m_{2}+\cdots+m_{r}$
\end_inset

.
 Then by the previous argument, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x_{1},\dots,x_{n}+\varepsilon)=(m_{1}+\varepsilon h_{1})+(m_{2}+\varepsilon h_{2})+\cdots+(m_{r}+\varepsilon h_{r}),
\]

\end_inset

where we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{i}$
\end_inset

 by the argument above if 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\mid m_{i}$
\end_inset

 and set 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{i}=0$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\not\mid m_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x_{1},\dots,x_{n}+\varepsilon)=f(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})+\varepsilon g(x_{1},\dots,x_{n}),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $g=h_{1}+h_{2}+\cdots+h_{r}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theoremweaknullstellensatz}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Weak Nullstellensatz) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be an algebraically closed field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subseteq K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

 be an ideal satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}(I)=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $I=K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Proof Summary: 
\series default
We prove that if 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a proper ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}(I)\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 Given 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in K$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ev}_{a}:K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]\to K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n-1}]$
\end_inset

 be the unique ring homomorphism given by mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\mapsto a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\mapsto x_{i}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,n-1$
\end_inset

.
 We first prove that claim that if 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is algebraically closed and 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a proper ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

, then there is an 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in K$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ev}_{a}(I)$
\end_inset

 is a proper ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n-1}]$
\end_inset

.
 Once we prove this claim, an easy induction gives elements 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},\dots,a_{n}\in K$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ev}_{a_{1}}(\mbox{Ev}_{a_{2}}(\cdots\mbox{Ev}_{a_{n}}(I))\cdots)$
\end_inset

 is a proper ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 But the only proper ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\{0\}$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ev}_{a_{1}}(\mbox{Ev}_{a_{2}}(\cdots\mbox{Ev}_{a_{n}}(I))\cdots)=\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{1},\dots,a_{n})\in\mathbf{V}(I)$
\end_inset

.
 We conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}(I)\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

, and therefore the theorem will follow.
 To prove the claim, we break it into two cases:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Case 1.
 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $I\cap K[x_{n}]\neq\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Pick nonzero 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in I\cap K[x_{n}]$
\end_inset

 and express it as 
\begin_inset Formula $f=c\prod_{i=1}^{r}(x_{n}-b_{i})^{m_{i}}$
\end_inset

 (this is where we use the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is algebraically closed).
 We must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ev}_{b_{i}}(I)$
\end_inset

 be a proper ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n-1}]$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 To see why, suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ev}_{b_{i}}(I)=K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n-1}]$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 Then for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 there is 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{i}\in I$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{i}(x_{1},\dots,x_{n-1},b_{i})=1$
\end_inset

.
 Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1=B_{i}(x_{1},\dots,x_{n-1},b_{i})=B_{i}(x_{1},\dots,x_{n-1},x_{n}-(x_{n}-b_{i}))=B_{i}+A_{i}(x_{n}-b_{i})
\]

\end_inset

for some 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}\in K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

.
 Since this holds for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,r$
\end_inset

, we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1=\prod_{i=1}^{r}(A_{i}(x_{n}-b_{i})+B_{i})^{m_{i}}=A\prod_{i=1}^{r}(x_{n}-b_{i})^{m_{i}}+B,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\prod_{i=1}^{r}A_{i}^{m_{i}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B\in I$
\end_inset

.
 This and 
\begin_inset Formula $\prod_{i=1}^{r}(x_{n}-b_{i})^{m_{i}}=c^{-1}f\in I$
\end_inset

 implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $1\in I$
\end_inset

, which contradicts the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a proper ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ev}_{b_{i}}(I)$
\end_inset

 is a proper ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n-1}]$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 This 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the desired 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Case 2.
 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $I\cap K[x_{n}]=\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{g_{1},\dots,g_{t}\}$
\end_inset

 be a Gröbner basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 for lex order with 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}>\cdots>x_{n}$
\end_inset

 and write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g_{i}=c_{i}(x_{n})x^{\alpha_{i}}+\mbox{terms}<x^{\alpha_{i}},\label{eq:1-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}(x_{n})\in K[x_{n}]$
\end_inset

 is nonzero and 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\alpha_{i}}$
\end_inset

 is a monomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},\dots,x_{n-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Now pick 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in K$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}(a)\neq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 This is possible since algebraically closed fields are infinite.
 It is easy to see that the polynomials
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bar{g}_{i}=g_{i}(x_{1},\dots,x_{n-1},a)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
form a basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ev}_{a}(I)$
\end_inset

.
 Substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}=a$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

equation~(
\backslash
ref{eq:1-1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, one easily sees that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LT}(\bar{g}_{i})=c_{i}(a)x^{\alpha_{i}}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}(a)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 This shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LT}(\bar{g}_{i})$
\end_inset

 is nonconstant for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{g}_{i}$
\end_inset

 form a Gröbner basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ev}_{a}(I)$
\end_inset

.
 Assuming the claim, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $1\notin\mbox{Ev}_{a}(I)$
\end_inset

 since no 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LT}(\bar{g}_{i})$
\end_inset

 can divide 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ev}_{a}(I)$
\end_inset

 is a proper ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n-1}]$
\end_inset

, which is what we wanted to show.
 Note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $I\cap K[x_{n}]\neq\{0\}$
\end_inset

, then for some 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 we'd have 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{j}=c_{j}(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{j}(x_{n})\in K[x_{n}]$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{g}_{j}=c_{j}(a)$
\end_inset

 becomes a unit, and would generate the unit ideal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To prove the claim, take 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i},g_{j}\in G$
\end_inset

 and consider the polynomial
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S=c_{j}(x_{n})\frac{x^{\gamma}}{x^{\alpha_{i}}}g_{i}-c_{i}(x_{n})\frac{x^{\gamma}}{x^{\alpha_{j}}}g_{j},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\gamma}=\mbox{lcm}(x^{\alpha_{i}},x^{\alpha_{j}})$
\end_inset

.
 By construction, 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\gamma}>\mbox{LT}(S)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $S\in I$
\end_inset

, it has a standard representation 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\sum_{\ell=1}^{t}A_{\ell}g_{\ell}$
\end_inset

.
 Then evaluating at 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}=a$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{j}(a)\frac{x^{\gamma}}{x^{\alpha_{i}}}\bar{g}_{i}-c_{i}(a)\frac{x^{\gamma}}{x^{\alpha_{j}}}\bar{g}_{j}=\bar{S}=\sum_{\ell=1}^{t}\bar{A}_{\ell}\bar{g}_{\ell}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LT}(\bar{g}_{i})=c_{i}(a)x^{\alpha_{i}}$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{S}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $S(\bar{g}_{i},\bar{g}_{j})$
\end_inset

 up to the nonzero constant 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}(a)c_{j}(a)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x^{\gamma}>\mbox{LT}(S)\geq\mbox{LT}(A_{\ell}g_{\ell}),\quad A_{\ell}g_{\ell}\neq0
\]

\end_inset

implies that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x^{\gamma}>\mbox{LT}(\bar{A}_{\ell}\bar{g}_{\ell}),\quad\bar{A}_{\ell}\bar{g}_{\ell}\neq0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\gamma}=\mbox{lcm}(\mbox{LM}(\bar{g}_{i}),\mbox{LM}(\bar{g}_{j}))$
\end_inset

, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $S(\bar{g}_{i},\bar{g}_{j})$
\end_inset

 has an lcm representation for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j$
\end_inset

 and hence is a Gröbner basis.
 This proves the claim and completes the proof of the theorem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We will prove the theorem in contrapositive form: If 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a proper ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}(I)\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 Given 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in K$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ev}_{a}:K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]\to K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n-1}]$
\end_inset

 be the unique ring homomorphism given by mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\mapsto a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\mapsto x_{i}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,n-1$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ev}_{a}$
\end_inset

 is surjective, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ev}_{a}(I)$
\end_inset

 is an ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n-1}]$
\end_inset

.
 The key step is the following claim
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Claim.
 
\series default
If 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is algebraically closed and 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a proper ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

, then there is an 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in K$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ev}_{a}(I)$
\end_inset

 is a proper ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n-1}]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Once we prove this claim, an easy induction gives elements 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},\dots,a_{n}\in K$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ev}_{a_{1}}(\mbox{Ev}_{a_{2}}(\cdots\mbox{Ev}_{a_{n}}(I))\cdots)$
\end_inset

 is a proper ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 But the only proper ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\{0\}$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ev}_{a_{1}}(\mbox{Ev}_{a_{2}}(\cdots\mbox{Ev}_{a_{n}}(I))\cdots)=\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{1},\dots,a_{n})\in\mathbf{V}(I)$
\end_inset

.
 We conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}(I)\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

, and therefore the theorem will follow.
 To prove the claim, there are two cases, depending on the size of 
\begin_inset Formula $I\cap K[x_{n}]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Case 1.
 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $I\cap K[x_{n}]\neq\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in I\cap K[x_{n}]$
\end_inset

 be nonzero, and note that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is nonconstant, since otherwise 
\begin_inset Formula $1\in I\cap K[x_{n}]\subseteq I$
\end_inset

, contradicting the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a proper ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is algebraically closed, 
\begin_inset Formula $f=c\prod_{i=1}^{r}(x_{n}-b_{i})^{m_{i}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $c,b_{1},\dots,b_{r}\in K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ev}_{b_{i}}(I)=K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n-1}]$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 Then for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 there is 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{i}\in I$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{i}(x_{1},\dots,x_{n-1},b_{i})=1$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1=B_{i}(x_{1},\dots,x_{n-1},b_{i})=B_{i}(x_{1},\dots,x_{n-1},x_{n}-(x_{n}-b_{i}))=B_{i}+A_{i}(x_{n}-b_{i})
\]

\end_inset

for some 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}\in K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

.
 Since this holds for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,r$
\end_inset

, we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1=\prod_{i=1}^{r}(A_{i}(x_{n}-b_{i})+B_{i})^{m_{i}}=A\prod_{i=1}^{r}(x_{n}-b_{i})^{m_{i}}+B,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\prod_{i=1}^{r}A_{i}^{m_{i}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B\in I$
\end_inset

.
 This and 
\begin_inset Formula $\prod_{i=1}^{r}(x_{n}-b_{i})^{m_{i}}=c^{-1}f\in I$
\end_inset

 implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $1\in I$
\end_inset

, which contradicts the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a proper ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ev}_{b_{i}}(I)$
\end_inset

 is a proper ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n-1}]$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 This 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the desired 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Case 2.
 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $I\cap K[x_{n}]=\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{g_{1},\dots,g_{t}\}$
\end_inset

 be a Gröbner basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 for lex order with 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}>\cdots>x_{n}$
\end_inset

 and write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g_{i}=c_{i}(x_{n})x^{\alpha_{i}}+\mbox{terms}<x^{\alpha_{i}},\label{eq:1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}(x_{n})\in K[x_{n}]$
\end_inset

 is nonzero and 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\alpha_{i}}$
\end_inset

 is a monomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},\dots,x_{n-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Now pick 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in K$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}(a)\neq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 This is possible since algebraically closed fields are infinite.
 It is easy to see that the polynomials
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bar{g}_{i}=g_{i}(x_{1},\dots,x_{n-1},a)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
form a basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ev}_{a}(I)$
\end_inset

.
 Substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}=a$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

equation~(
\backslash
ref{eq:1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, one easily sees that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LT}(\bar{g}_{i})=c_{i}(a)x^{\alpha_{i}}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}(a)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 This shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LT}(\bar{g}_{i})$
\end_inset

 is nonconstant for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{g}_{i}$
\end_inset

 form a Gröbner basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ev}_{a}(I)$
\end_inset

.
 Assuming the claim, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $1\notin\mbox{Ev}_{a}(I)$
\end_inset

 since no 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LT}(\bar{g}_{i})$
\end_inset

 can divide 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ev}_{a}(I)$
\end_inset

 is a proper ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n-1}]$
\end_inset

, which is what we wanted to show.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To prove the claim, take 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i},g_{j}\in G$
\end_inset

 and consider the polynomial
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S=c_{j}(x_{n})\frac{x^{\gamma}}{x^{\alpha_{i}}}g_{i}-c_{i}(x_{n})\frac{x^{\gamma}}{x^{\alpha_{j}}}g_{j},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\gamma}=\mbox{lcm}(x^{\alpha_{i}},x^{\alpha_{j}})$
\end_inset

.
 By construction, 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\gamma}>\mbox{LT}(S)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $S\in I$
\end_inset

, it has a standard representation 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\sum_{\ell=1}^{t}A_{\ell}g_{\ell}$
\end_inset

.
 Then evaluating at 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}=a$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{j}(a)\frac{x^{\gamma}}{x^{\alpha_{i}}}\bar{g}_{i}-c_{i}(a)\frac{x^{\gamma}}{x^{\alpha_{j}}}\bar{g}_{j}=\bar{S}=\sum_{\ell=1}^{t}\bar{A}_{\ell}\bar{g}_{\ell}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{LT}(\bar{g}_{i})=c_{i}(a)x^{\alpha_{i}}$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{S}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $S(\bar{g}_{i},\bar{g}_{j})$
\end_inset

 up to the nonzero constant 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}(a)c_{j}(a)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x^{\gamma}>\mbox{LT}(S)\geq\mbox{LT}(A_{\ell}g_{\ell}),\quad A_{\ell}g_{\ell}\neq0
\]

\end_inset

implies that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x^{\gamma}>\mbox{LT}(\bar{A}_{\ell}\bar{g}_{\ell}),\quad\bar{A}_{\ell}\bar{g}_{\ell}\neq0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\gamma}=\mbox{lcm}(\mbox{LM}(\bar{g}_{i}),\mbox{LM}(\bar{g}_{j}))$
\end_inset

, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $S(\bar{g}_{i},\bar{g}_{j})$
\end_inset

 has an lcm representation for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j$
\end_inset

 and hence is a Gröbner basis.
 This proves the claim and completes the proof of the theorem.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

